  "23-19": (
    caption: [Metabolic cooperation between skeletal muscle and the liver: the Cori cycle. Extremely active muscles use glycogen as their energy source, generating lactate via glycolysis. During recovery, some of this lactate is transported to the liver and converted to glucose via gluconeogenesis. This glucose is released to the blood and returned to the muscles to replenish their glycogen stores. The overall pathway (glucose S lactate S glucose) constitutes the Cori cycle. 1 (cid:3)m],
    path: "../fig/image_place_holder.png"
  ),
  "23-20": (
    caption: [Electron micrograph of heart muscle. In the profuse mito- chondria of heart tissue, pyruvate (from glucose), fatty acids, and ketone bodies are oxidized to drive ATP synthesis. This steady aerobic metabo- lism allows the human heart to pump blood at a rate of nearly 6 L/min, or about 350 L/h—or 200 3 106 L of blood over 70 years. c23HormonalRegulationAndIntegrationOfMammalianMetabolism.indd Page 949 05/10/12 1:17 PM user-F408 c23HormonalRegulationAndIntegrationOfMammalianMetabolism.indd Page 949 05/10/12 1:17 PM user-F408 /Users/user-F408/Desktop /Users/user-F408/Desktop 23.2 Tissue-Specific Metabolism: The Division of Labor 949],
